{#
  Object detail container — swapped into #results-slot when a row is clicked.

  Layout (search sidebar sits to the left of this, outside the container):
    Two stacked CSS grids (one per row) with a draggable handle between
    them — same `grid-template-columns: 1fr 1.3fr 1.3fr 1fr` on both, so
    column widths line up across rows. Side panels (basic-info,
    position-residuals/periodogram/airmass, radar, aladin) sit in
    1-fr columns; the centre panels (light curve, stamps) span two
    1.3-fr columns each. Row 1: basic-information | light curve | position
    residuals. Row 2: radar plot | stamps | Aladin.

    The two grids are split (rather than one 2-row grid) so a resize
    handle can sit between them and pin explicit pixel heights on each
    row when the user drags. Default row sizing stays auto (LC drives
    row 1 via its flex-col content; row-2 side panels' aspect-ratio
    drives row 2). Inline `grid-template-columns` so it works without
    depending on whether Tailwind's JIT picked up the arbitrary
    `[…fr]` class.
#}
<style>
  /*
    Mobile layout (< Tailwind lg = 1024 px): collapse the two-row grid
    into a single stacked column. We use `display: contents` to flatten
    the row hierarchy so every panel becomes a direct flex child of
    `#object-detail`, then sequence them with `order:` to get the
    requested mobile reading order:
      basic-info → probabilities → light curve →
      position residuals/periodogram/airmass → stamps → aladin → xmatch
    Drag-resize handles are hidden because side-by-side resize doesn't
    apply to a single column.

    Chart-bearing panels carry an explicit `height` (not `min-height`):
    the inner cards use `tw-h-full` (height: 100%) which only resolves
    against a definite parent height. With only `min-height` on the
    slot, the parent's height stays `auto` and `tw-h-full` collapses
    to 0 — the visible symptom is "stamps and aladin not showing"
    because the canvas wrappers inside (`flex-1 min-h-0`) inherit a
    zero height from their content-sized ancestor. Explicit `height`
    pins the slot, the inner card fills it via `tw-h-full`, and the
    canvas wrappers grow into the remaining space.
    Basic-info uses `min-height` so its variable-length info table
    isn't capped — it scrolls inside the slot via `tw-overflow-auto`.
    Crossmatch is the collapsible summary, sized by its own content.
  */
  @media (max-width: 1023px) {
    #rows-wrapper,
    #detail-row-1,
    #detail-row-2 {
      display: contents;
    }
    #row-resize-handle,
    #row-resize-handle-2 {
      display: none;
    }
    #basic-info-slot   { order: 1; min-height: 18rem; }
    #radar-slot        { order: 2; height: 22rem; }
    #lightcurve-slot   { order: 3; height: 31.2rem; }
    #residuals-cell    { order: 4; height: 22rem; }
    #stamps-slot       { order: 5; height: 16rem; }
    #aladin-slot       { order: 6; height: 22rem; }
    #crossmatch-slot   { order: 7; }
  }
</style>

<div
  id="object-detail"
  class="tw-flex tw-flex-col tw-gap-3"
  data-oid="{{ oid }}"
  data-survey-id="{{ survey_id }}"
  {% if classifier %}data-classifier="{{ classifier }}"{% endif %}
>

  {#
    Nav row (Back / OID dots / prev-next arrows + position) used to live
    here as the first child. It was promoted to the global header in
    index.html.jinja (#detail-nav-bar) so the detail panels can use the
    full vertical space. object_nav.js shows/hides the bar based on
    whether `#object-detail` (this element) is in the DOM.
  #}
  {#
    Neither row uses inline `aspect-ratio` on the side panels: aspect-ratio
    on a grid item fixes its block-size and prevents `align-self: stretch`
    from kicking in, so the side panels would stay square while the rest
    of the row grew or shrank. Both rows use `grid-template-rows:
    minmax(0, 1fr)` (set on the grid container) plus the resize-handle
    JS pinning the container's height — that gives the panels a
    synchronized track height to stretch into. Stamps still use
    width-aspect-square children for individual stamp images, but each
    one is wrapped in a flex layout that lets it shrink to
    `min(cell_width, available_height)` when row 2 is dragged smaller.

    The drag-handle wrapper has no internal gap; each handle's own
    height provides the row separation that `tw-gap-3` gave when the
    rows were a single grid.
  #}
  <div id="rows-wrapper" class="tw-flex tw-flex-col">
    {#
      `minmax(0, …fr)` instead of bare `…fr` so each track is sized purely by
      the fr ratios, not by the item's min-content. In the prior single-grid
      layout column 2 saw both LC (row 1) and stamps (row 2) in the same
      track, balancing min-content across rows. Splitting into two grids
      broke that — stamps' fixed-aspect children would push row 2's fr
      tracks wider than row 1's identical fr template, and the column edges
      would drift. The minmax(0,…) wrapper lets the track shrink to 0 if
      needed, so column widths come out the same on both rows.
      `tw-overflow-hidden` clips inner overflow when the row is shrunk
      below its natural content min — without it, the LC's
      `min-h-[15.84rem]` canvas wrapper escapes the row's box and
      visually overlaps row 2.
      `tw-min-h-0` is the missing piece for the drag-to-resize: as a flex
      child, the row's implicit `min-height: auto` resolves to its
      content's min-content (~290 px from LC's flex-col children), which
      *blocks* an explicit `style.height` set below that — so dragging
      down (height > min-content) worked, but dragging up (height <
      min-content) silently no-op'd. Pinning min-height to 0 lets the
      explicit height win in both directions.
    #}
    <div
      id="detail-row-1"
      class="tw-grid tw-gap-3 tw-overflow-hidden tw-min-h-0"
      style="grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) minmax(0, 1.3fr) minmax(0, 1.3fr) minmax(0, 1fr); grid-template-rows: minmax(0, 1fr);"
    >
      <div
        id="basic-info-slot"
        class="tw-col-span-1 tw-overflow-auto tw-min-h-0"
        hx-get="{{ API_URL }}/htmx/object_information?oid={{ oid }}&survey_id={{ survey_id }}"
        hx-trigger="load"
        hx-swap="innerHTML"
      >
        <div class="tw-text-xs tw-text-text-muted tw-p-4">Loading basic information…</div>
      </div>
      <div
        id="lightcurve-slot"
        class="tw-col-span-2"
        hx-get="{{ API_URL }}/htmx/lightcurve?oid={{ oid }}&survey_id={{ survey_id }}"
        hx-trigger="load"
        hx-swap="innerHTML"
      >
        <div class="tw-bg-bg-card tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded tw-p-4 tw-text-xs tw-text-text-muted">
          Loading light curve…
        </div>
      </div>
      {#
        Position residuals + periodogram + airmass share the same grid cell.
        Only one is visible at a time; togglePeriodogramPanel and
        toggleAirmassPanel manage the mutual-exclusion (and which button is
        highlighted) via tw-hidden. Periodogram is driven from the LC
        toolbar's Periodogram button; Airmass from the Basic Information
        panel's Airmass button. Panels carry their templates inline so the
        canvas is ready for Chart.js the first time the toggle flips it on.
      #}
      <div
        id="residuals-cell"
        class="tw-col-span-1 tw-min-h-0 tw-min-w-0"
      >
        <div
          id="coord-residuals-slot"
          class="tw-h-full"
          hx-get="{{ API_URL }}/htmx/coord_residuals?oid={{ oid }}&survey_id={{ survey_id }}"
          hx-trigger="load"
          hx-swap="innerHTML"
        >
          <div class="tw-bg-bg-card tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded tw-p-4 tw-text-xs tw-text-text-muted">
            Loading position residuals…
          </div>
        </div>
        <div id="periodogram-slot" class="tw-hidden tw-h-full">
          {% include "periodogram/periodogramPreview.html.jinja" %}
        </div>
        <div id="airmass-slot" class="tw-hidden tw-h-full">
          {% include "airmass/airmassPanel.html.jinja" %}
        </div>
        <div id="color-evolution-slot" class="tw-hidden tw-h-full">
          {% include "color_evolution/colorEvolutionPreview.html.jinja" %}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    {#
      Draggable resize handle. Pointer-events flow: pointerdown captures
      the pointer on the handle so subsequent move/up events keep firing
      even when the cursor strays outside the bar (or off-screen during a
      fast drag). Δy adjusts row 1 by +Δ and row 2 by −Δ → total height is
      preserved, the panel rows just trade vertical space. Both rows clamp
      at MIN_ROW_PX so the user can't shrink either to zero. Double-click
      clears the inline heights and returns to auto-sizing.
    #}
    <div
      id="row-resize-handle"
      class="tw-flex tw-items-center tw-justify-center hover:tw-bg-bg-tertiary tw-transition-colors tw-rounded"
      style="height: 0.75rem; cursor: row-resize; touch-action: none;"
      title="Drag to resize the top and bottom rows. Double-click to reset."
      role="separator"
      aria-orientation="horizontal"
      aria-label="Resize top and bottom rows"
    >
      <div style="height: 3px; width: 4rem; border-radius: 9999px; background: #333333;"></div>
    </div>

    <div
      id="detail-row-2"
      class="tw-grid tw-gap-3 tw-overflow-hidden tw-min-h-0"
      style="grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) minmax(0, 1.3fr) minmax(0, 1.3fr) minmax(0, 1fr); grid-template-rows: minmax(0, 1fr);"
    >
      <div
        id="radar-slot"
        class="tw-col-span-1 tw-min-h-0"
        hx-get="{{ API_URL }}/htmx/probability?oid={{ oid }}&survey_id={{ survey_id }}{% if classifier %}&classifier={{ classifier|urlencode }}{% endif %}"
        hx-trigger="load"
        hx-swap="innerHTML"
      >
        <div class="tw-bg-bg-card tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded tw-p-4 tw-text-xs tw-text-text-muted">
          Loading probabilities…
        </div>
      </div>
      <div
        id="stamps-slot"
        class="tw-col-span-2 tw-min-h-0"
        hx-get="{{ API_URL }}/htmx/stamps?oid={{ oid }}&survey_id={{ survey_id }}{% if identifier %}&identifier={{ identifier|urlencode }}{% endif %}"
        hx-trigger="load"
        hx-swap="innerHTML"
      >
        <div class="tw-bg-bg-card tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded tw-p-4 tw-text-xs tw-text-text-muted">
          Loading stamps…
        </div>
      </div>
      <div
        id="aladin-slot"
        class="tw-col-span-1 tw-min-h-0"
        hx-get="{{ API_URL }}/htmx/aladin?oid={{ oid }}&survey_id={{ survey_id }}"
        hx-trigger="load"
        hx-swap="innerHTML"
      >
        <div class="tw-bg-bg-card tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded tw-p-4 tw-text-xs tw-text-text-muted">
          Loading sky view…
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    {#
      Second draggable handle — sits between row 2 and the crossmatch
      panel and resizes row 2 the same way the first handle resizes row 1.
      Crossmatch is moved inside the wrapper so the handle's separator
      replaces the previous flex gap (handle provides spacing; no extra
      margin/gap needed).
    #}
    <div
      id="row-resize-handle-2"
      class="tw-flex tw-items-center tw-justify-center hover:tw-bg-bg-tertiary tw-transition-colors tw-rounded"
      style="height: 0.75rem; cursor: row-resize; touch-action: none;"
      title="Drag to resize the second row. Double-click to reset."
      role="separator"
      aria-orientation="horizontal"
      aria-label="Resize second row"
    >
      <div style="height: 3px; width: 4rem; border-radius: 9999px; background: #333333;"></div>
    </div>

    {#
      Crossmatch — full-width collapsible at the bottom of the detail page.
      Native <details>/<summary> handles the open/close UI; the fetch fires
      on `load` (not on toggle) so the data is already in the DOM by the
      time the user clicks the summary — no spinner-on-expand wait. The
      panel is `open` by default (the crossmatch is high-value), and because
      the fetch already fired on load it's populated immediately. Sources: the
      bulk CDS/NED crossmatch table (served from the page-load prefetch cache)
      plus catsHTM below. Lives inside the row-resize wrapper so handle-2 can
      sit between row 2 and this slot.
    #}
    <div id="crossmatch-slot">
    <details
      id="crossmatch-details"
      class="tw-bg-bg-card tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded"
      open
    >
      <summary
        class="tw-cursor-pointer tw-px-4 tw-py-3 tw-text-sm tw-font-medium tw-text-text-primary hover:tw-bg-bg-tertiary tw-flex tw-items-center tw-gap-2"
      >
        <span>Crossmatch</span>
        {#
          Hover card describing every crossmatched catalog. Reuses the
          `.panel-help` fixed-tooltip mechanism (positioned by panel_help.js)
          but keeps the summary's own title styling. preventDefault on the
          wrapper stops a click on the (?) / card from toggling the <details>;
          clicking the "Crossmatch" text still toggles normally.
        #}
        <span class="tw-relative tw-group panel-help" data-tooltip-side="left"
              onclick="event.preventDefault();event.stopPropagation();">
          <span class="tw-text-text-muted tw-text-xs tw-cursor-help" tabindex="0">(?)</span>
          <div role="tooltip"
               class="tw-hidden group-hover:tw-block group-focus-within:tw-block tw-fixed tw-z-50 tw-w-80 tw-max-w-[calc(100vw-2rem)] tw-max-h-[80vh] tw-overflow-y-auto tw-bg-bg-card tw-border tw-border-border tw-rounded tw-p-3 tw-text-xs tw-font-normal tw-text-text-primary tw-normal-case tw-shadow-lg tw-leading-relaxed">
            <div class="tw-font-semibold tw-mb-1">Crossmatched catalogs</div>
            <div class="tw-mb-2 tw-text-text-secondary">Bulk CDS XMatch + NED, run server-side and prefetched so this opens instantly. Matches show below ordered stars → AGN → host; markers appear in the Aladin panel, colour-coded by category.</div>
            <div class="tw-font-semibold tw-flex tw-items-center tw-gap-1.5"><span class="tw-inline-block tw-rounded-full" style="width:8px;height:8px;background:{{ xmatch_colors['stellar'] }}"></span>Stellar (Milky Way)</div>
            <ul class="tw-list-disc tw-list-inside tw-text-text-secondary tw-mb-1.5">
              <li>Gaia DR3 — parallax, proper motion, G, BP−RP</li>
              <li>AAVSO VSX — variable type, period</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="tw-font-semibold tw-flex tw-items-center tw-gap-1.5"><span class="tw-inline-block tw-rounded-full" style="width:8px;height:8px;background:{{ xmatch_colors['agn'] }}"></span>AGN / quasars</div>
            <ul class="tw-list-disc tw-list-inside tw-text-text-secondary tw-mb-1.5">
              <li>Milliquas (Million Quasars) — class, z, radio/X-ray flags</li>
              <li>Véron-Cetty QSO · SDSS DR16 QSO</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="tw-font-semibold tw-flex tw-items-center tw-gap-1.5"><span class="tw-inline-block tw-rounded-full" style="width:8px;height:8px;background:{{ xmatch_colors['host'] }}"></span>Host galaxies (redshift &amp; morphology)</div>
            <ul class="tw-list-disc tw-list-inside tw-text-text-secondary tw-mb-1.5">
              <li>DESI DR1, SDSS DR16, 6dFGS, GAMA DR4, 2MRS, WiggleZ, zCOSMOS, VIPERS PDR2, OzDES DR1, 2dFGRS, HECATE, GLADE v2</li>
              <li>HyperLEDA — morphology / size · NED &amp; SIMBAD — names, types, redshifts</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="tw-text-text-secondary">Plus catsHTM (shown below): positional crossmatch against Gaia, PS1, AllWISE, 2MASS, and more.</div>
          </div>
        </span>
        <span class="tw-text-xs tw-text-text-muted">click to collapse</span>
      </summary>
      <div
        id="crossmatch-body"
        class="tw-px-4 tw-pb-4 tw-pt-3 tw-text-xs tw-border-t tw-border-border"
        hx-get="{{ API_URL }}/htmx/crossmatch?oid={{ oid }}&survey_id={{ survey_id }}"
        hx-trigger="load"
        hx-swap="innerHTML"
      >
        {#
          Expressive loading state: a cold (un-prefetched) object fires ~20 live
          CDS XMatch + NED queries, so the wait names every catalog being hit,
          grouped by category. The list comes from xmatch_catalogs() so it tracks
          the registry. Replaced wholesale once /htmx/crossmatch returns.
        #}
        {%- set cats = xmatch_catalogs() %}
        <div class="tw-text-text-secondary tw-py-2 tw-text-[11px] tw-leading-relaxed">
          <div class="tw-text-text-primary tw-mb-2 tw-flex tw-items-center tw-gap-2">
            {# CSS ring spinner — Font Awesome isn't loaded in this app, so the
               old fa-spinner rendered nothing. tw-animate-spin (compiled) drives
               the rotation; the ring itself is inline styles so it can't be
               purged. #}
            <span class="tw-inline-block tw-animate-spin" style="width:14px;height:14px;border:2px solid rgba(237,237,237,0.25);border-top-color:#42a5f5;border-radius:9999px;flex-shrink:0"></span>
            <span>Querying {{ cats.total }} catalogs &mdash; CDS XMatch + NED&hellip;</span>
          </div>
          {% for label, color, names in cats.groups %}
            {% if names %}
              <div class="tw-mb-1 tw-flex tw-items-baseline tw-gap-1.5">
                <span class="tw-inline-block tw-rounded-full tw-shrink-0" style="width:8px;height:8px;background:{{ color }};transform:translateY(1px)"></span>
                <span><span class="tw-text-text-primary tw-font-semibold">{{ label }}</span> &middot; {{ names | join(", ") }}</span>
              </div>
            {% endif %}
          {% endfor %}
          <div class="tw-text-text-muted tw-mt-2">Results are usually prefetched on the results page, so this is normally instant; a direct deep-link computes them now.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
    </div>
  </div>

  {# Overlay slot for the "Show features" modal — stays empty until the
     button's hx-get populates it, and the close button clears it again. #}
  <div id="features-modal"></div>

  {# Same pattern for the per-detection AVRO viewer (stamps panel button).
     ZTF-only data, but the slot is unconditional: the LSST path renders
     a "AVRO is ZTF-only" message inside it instead of a separate gate. #}
  <div id="avro-modal"></div>

</div>

<script>
(function () {
  // Re-runs on every detail-view swap because the <script> is part of the
  // fragment. IIFE-scoped so each run has its own refs; old listeners die
  // with the old DOM elements. Pointer events (not mouse-only) so it works
  // for touch + pen too; setPointerCapture keeps the move/up stream tied
  // to the handle if the cursor strays during a fast drag.
  // Two draggable separators: one between row 1 and row 2, another
  // between row 2 and the crossmatch panel. Each binds the same
  // pattern — drag adjusts the row *above* the handle; the rows below
  // stay at content-driven heights and ride along with the line.
  //
  // Implementation notes (earlier attempts misbehaved on the shrink
  // direction, so this is deliberately defensive):
  //   - Direct math: the row's top is fixed during the drag, so the
  //     new height is just `mouseY - row.top`. No accumulated delta
  //     state, no `startH` baseline that could go stale if the layout
  //     reflows mid-drag.
  //   - `setProperty('height', …, 'important')` plus the matching
  //     `min-height: 0 !important` and `max-height: … !important`
  //     guarantee the box is *exactly* the requested size. Without all
  //     three, a flex child's implicit `min-height: auto` (which can
  //     resolve to the content's min-content even with overflow:hidden,
  //     in some engines) silently floors the explicit height — drag
  //     down grew past the floor and worked, drag up shrunk *below* it
  //     and was a no-op.
  //   - rAF coalesces pointermove bursts so high-rate mice don't queue
  //     up dozens of layout passes per frame.
  const MIN_ROW_PX = 120;
  // Row heights persist across object navigation via sessionStorage —
  // every detail swap re-runs this script, and reading the stored value
  // here propagates the user's last drag to the new view. Cleared on
  // dblclick (per row). sessionStorage so it lives only for the tab.
  const STORAGE_KEY = "objectDetailRowHeights";

  function loadHeights() {
    try { return JSON.parse(sessionStorage.getItem(STORAGE_KEY) || "{}"); }
    catch (_) { return {}; }
  }
  function saveHeight(key, value) {
    const data = loadHeights();
    if (value == null) delete data[key]; else data[key] = value;
    try { sessionStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, JSON.stringify(data)); }
    catch (_) { /* quota / disabled / private mode — silently skip */ }
  }

  function setHeight(row, px) {
    const v = px + "px";
    row.style.setProperty("height", v, "important");
    row.style.setProperty("min-height", "0", "important");
    row.style.setProperty("max-height", v, "important");
  }
  function clearHeight(row) {
    row.style.removeProperty("height");
    row.style.removeProperty("min-height");
    row.style.removeProperty("max-height");
  }

  function bindRowResize(handle, row, storageKey) {
    if (!handle || !row) return;

    handle.addEventListener("pointerdown", (e) => {
      // Left button only on mouse (e.button === 0); touch / pen always pass.
      if (e.pointerType === "mouse" && e.button !== 0) return;
      e.preventDefault();
      handle.setPointerCapture(e.pointerId);
      const rowTop = row.getBoundingClientRect().top;
      let rafId = 0;
      let pendingY = e.clientY;
      let lastH = null;

      function apply() {
        rafId = 0;
        // newH = mouseY - rowTop: the line follows the mouse exactly,
        // and the row's bottom edge sits where the cursor is (modulo
        // the floor clamp).
        const newH = Math.max(MIN_ROW_PX, pendingY - rowTop);
        setHeight(row, newH);
        lastH = newH;
      }
      function onMove(ev) {
        if (ev.pointerId !== e.pointerId) return;
        pendingY = ev.clientY;
        if (!rafId) rafId = requestAnimationFrame(apply);
      }
      function onUp(ev) {
        if (ev.pointerId !== e.pointerId) return;
        handle.removeEventListener("pointermove", onMove);
        handle.removeEventListener("pointerup", onUp);
        handle.removeEventListener("pointercancel", onUp);
        if (rafId) cancelAnimationFrame(rafId);
        try { handle.releasePointerCapture(e.pointerId); } catch (_) { /* noop */ }
        document.body.style.userSelect = "";
        document.body.style.cursor = "";
        // Persist once per drag, at release. Mid-drag writes would just
        // burn cycles since storage is only read on script re-init.
        if (lastH != null) saveHeight(storageKey, lastH);
      }
      // userSelect:none on body prevents text-selection drag; the global
      // cursor mirrors the handle's so the visual stays consistent even
      // if the pointer wanders off the handle during a fast drag.
      document.body.style.userSelect = "none";
      document.body.style.cursor = "row-resize";
      handle.addEventListener("pointermove", onMove);
      handle.addEventListener("pointerup", onUp);
      handle.addEventListener("pointercancel", onUp);
    });

    // Double-click clears all three inline properties so the row returns
    // to its content-driven default — and forgets the saved size so the
    // next object navigation starts fresh too.
    handle.addEventListener("dblclick", () => {
      clearHeight(row);
      saveHeight(storageKey, null);
    });
  }

  const row1 = document.getElementById("detail-row-1");
  const row2 = document.getElementById("detail-row-2");
  bindRowResize(document.getElementById("row-resize-handle"), row1, "row1");
  bindRowResize(document.getElementById("row-resize-handle-2"), row2, "row2");

  // Restore on swap-in. Mobile (`display: contents` on the rows) ignores
  // the inline height — the value sits dormant and re-applies if the
  // viewport returns to desktop. Numeric guard so a malformed stored
  // value can't poison the layout.
  const saved = loadHeights();
  if (row1 && typeof saved.row1 === "number" && saved.row1 >= MIN_ROW_PX) {
    setHeight(row1, saved.row1);
  }
  if (row2 && typeof saved.row2 === "number" && saved.row2 >= MIN_ROW_PX) {
    setHeight(row2, saved.row2);
  }
})();
</script>
